com.analog.lyric.collect

Class UniquePriorityQueue<E>

  • java.lang.Object
    • java.util.AbstractCollection<E>
      • java.util.AbstractQueue<E>
        • com.analog.lyric.collect.AbstractKeyedPriorityQueue<E,E>
          • com.analog.lyric.collect.UniquePriorityQueue<E>
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    java.io.Serializable, java.lang.Iterable<E>, java.util.Collection<E>, java.util.Queue<E>

    @NotThreadSafe
public class UniquePriorityQueue<E>
extends AbstractKeyedPriorityQueue<E,E>
implements java.io.Serializable
    A priority queue that only holds one instance of an element.

    This is similar to PriorityQueue except that:

    • Calls to AbstractKeyedPriorityQueue.offer(Object) and AbstractKeyedPriorityQueue.add(Object) will return false when element is already in the queue.
    • Calls to contains(Object) are O(1) instead of O(n).
    • When two elements have the same priority, the first element added will be returned by AbstractQueue.remove() et al.
    Since:
    0.05
    See Also:
    KeyedPriorityQueue, Serialized Form

        public UniquePriorityQueue(int initialCapacity,
                   @Nullable
                   java.util.Comparator<? super E> priorityComparator)
        Constructs empty queue.
        Parameters:
        initialCapacity - provides a hint as to the intended size of the queue.
        priorityComparator - defines the priority ordering among elements. If null, then natural ordering will be used and all elements must implement Comparable and must be comparable to existing elements in the queue.

      • UniquePriorityQueue

        public UniquePriorityQueue(java.util.Collection<? extends E> collection)
        Constructs queue with elements from collection.
        Parameters:
        collection - specifies the elements to add to the queue which will be added in the same order as the collection's iterator. If the collection is a SortedSet, then its comparator will be used to determine priorities. Otherwise the natural order will be used (see UniquePriorityQueue(int, Comparator)).
